 — President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva (PT) stated that he intends to move forward with the regulation of all digital platforms in order to supposedly “prevent foreign interference in the Brazilian electoral process” and “contain disinformation in Brazil”

 The statement was made after a bilateral meeting with Spain’s socialist prime minister, Pedro Sánchez, in Barcelona, on the eve of an international gathering of leaders aligned with a progressive agenda. Lula emphasized that the regulation should be implemented this year, as soon as possible before the election. In his view, big tech companies try to treat what he considers “disinformation” as something “normal.”

“We now need to regulate everything that is digital so that we can ensure sovereignty for our country and prevent outside interference, especially in an election year. It is not possible to treat the industry of lies, verbal violence, and disinformation as normal or as freedom of expression, as has been happening around the world. Without rules, big techs will establish the era of digital colonialism. [...] Our data is extracted, monetized, and used to concentrate political and economic power in the hands of a handful of billionaires!”

 The president also linked the digital environment to rising violence and impacts on mental health, especially among children. According to his views, the virtual world “has become a toxic environment that affects the mental health of our youth,” citing the spread of hate speech as a factor worsening social conditions.

 Amid his international agenda, Lula is taking part in a meeting with heads of state who are part of the Democracy Forever Forum, created in 2024 with the aim of coordinating actions in response to the global rise of conservative forces, considered by the group to be far-right. Participants include leaders from Latin America, Europe, and Africa, focusing on issues such as disinformation, multilateralism, and inequality.

